{"/service/ndnp/iune/batch_iune_dove_ver03/data/sn90053031/00542864655/1908010401/0653.xml":{"full_text":"HEWS FROM IRELAND,\nAlt Happenings of Interest in\nthe Old Country.\nWhat It Being Dene at Home\u2014\nGastfp from All the Provinces.\nLEINSTER.\nDistinction for Kingstown V. S.\u2014\nMr. Johu Carr. Jr., veterinary surgeon\nto Kingstown Urban district, has been\nmade a Fellow of the Royal College of\nVeterinary Surgeons. London.\nThree Months for Housebreaking.\u2014\nA term of three months\u2019 imprisonment,\nwas inij>osed at Kingstown Police\nCourt on Joseph Mullen. Kelly's court,\ncharged with breaking into the house\n3 MeG4!lick's court, ami stealing 23s.\nand several articles of clothing, the\nproperty of Mrs. MeGuirke and Mrs.\nBe Illy.\nEx-P. M. r. Inspector I\u00bbend.\u2014 Ine\ndeath of Mr. Michael Lynam is an\nnounced at his residence, 54 Hadding\nton road. Demised was for many\nyears associated with the Dublin Met\nropolitan Pol in*, and was promoted to\nthe rank of inspector; He retired from\nactive duty a few years ago. and since\nthen lived in retirement.\nIn Service of Ireland.\u2014Notice of\nmotion appears in the agenda for the\nnext meeting of the North Dublin\nBoard of Guardians, under the name\nof Mr. Denis Dovle. that the? words\n\"I Seirhhis na h-Elreann\u201d (in the ser\nvice of Ireland) be printed over \u201cNorth\nDublin Union\u201d on nil note paper and\nenvelopes, and that the \u2018\u2018Anns of Dub\nlin\u201d tie the only insignia appearing on\nsuch stationery.\nFell Off Ladder and Died.\u2014At an\ninquest at the Mater Hospital on Sat\nurday on the body of Thomas Benson.\n40, a laborer of Upper Gloucester\nstreet, a verdict was returned of death\nfrom asphyxia, brought on by the pres\nsure of blood on the spinal cord. A\nrider commended the widow and fam\nily of the deceased to the consideration\nof his employer. Mr. Cunniffe. builder,\nNorth Circular road. It was stated\nthat deceased accidentally fell off a\nladder on the 10th Inst., while work\ning in his employer's yard.\nWho Stole the Child?\u2014-A strange\nstory of n child said to have been\nstolen is told by a woman named May\nAnne Kelly. Dominick street. She\nstates she had the child, aged about\neight months old. in her arms, when\na man whom she could not describe\nother than that he was tall and %ell\ndressed and a stranger, came up to\nher. and asked for the child to buy\nsweets or cakes for it, blit neltbe- him\nself nor the child returned.\nAn Unfounded Charge.\u2014Francis\nCummins, on being discharged in\nKingstown Police Court, the charge\nagainst him being that of uttering\nbase coin to Mrs. M. Ruddock, Black\nrock, asked the Bench what steps he\ncould take against that lady to re\ndeem his character. Mr. Swifte in\nformed him that Mrs. Ruddock ap\npeared to have made a bona-fide mis\ntake, and the matter of redress was\notie for the accused himself.\nFound Dead in Bed.\u2014Timothy\nO'Brien. 21 York street, aged about 24.\nwas found apparently dead in bed in\nhis room on Monday, lie was fully\ndressed at the time. At Mercer\u2019s Hos\npital Dr. Knapp, on examination, pro\nnounced him to be dead. Deceased\nwas a van driver, and a married man.\nand had been out of employment for\nthe past two years. His widow states\nthat he had been strange in bis man\nner lately, although apparently in fair\nbodily health. An Inquest will be held\nto-day.\nDumping Rubbish.'\u2014Mr. Justice Bar\nton on Saturday awarded Messrs.\nArmstrong and Co.. Ltd., paper mer\nchants, \u20ac90 compensation in respect of\nthe dumping of rubbish on the four\nacres of waste ground at Olonliffe\nroad. The case arose in the matter\nof Maurice Butterly. deceased, the\nMunster Bank. Ltd., v. Butter!v. A\nresident stated that the stuff deposited\nconsisted of ashpit refuse, dead oats\nand dogs, ami other objectionable mat\nter. The odor from the rubbish was\nat all times offensive. Messrs. Arm\nstrong estimated that It would cost\n\u00a3100 to have the rubbish removecL\nAn Institution\u2019s Liabilities.\u2014In the\n\u00ab*ase of tile Dublin Female Peniten-!\ntiary. North Circular road, the trustees 1\nof which last week applied for an j\norder that tlw* charity be no longer j\ncontinued, as it was being run at a\nloss, and the trustees were being sued\npersonally for debts amounting to\n\u00b1207. Mr. Justice Barton yesterday\naccepted a consent. Under the terms\nof this consent a sum of money is to\nbe raised ou mortgage to discharge\nexisting liabilities. His lordship also\nagreed to the resignation of the pres\nent trustees, and allowed the costa of j\nthe parties to the petition.\nWhat Drum Fete Brought.\u2014The j\nHon. Treasurer of the recent Drum\nfete has handed over ;417 for the ben\nefit of the Dntmcomlra Hospital, and\nat thv meeting of the committee a res\nolution was passed expressing appre-\nciarlon of the efforts of all who t<K>k\npart in the fete, which realized alto\ngether \u00a3567 Ids. lOd. A vote of thanks\nhas also been passed to Miss Ovlgh\nton-Williams and the pupils of the\nCollegiate School for a contribution of\n\u00a340 17s. 10d.. the proceeds of a sale\nand concert at Ilatfamlnes. The usual\nNew Year's entertainment by the La\ndies' Committee was approved of.\nAn nntenanted house, the property\nof Mrs. Byrne, Athboy, lias been de\nstroyed by fire, and a bullock was\nroasted to death. The animal was the\n(property of a Mr. Keane, and It Is\nstated that a claim for compensation\nwill be made.\nA memorial window to the late Mrs.\nLockett Ford has lw*en unveiled at St.\n\\Iauy's du*r< h. Ardee, In presence of\na representative congregation, and the\nsermon at which was preached by Rev.\nR.\u2019 M. Ffeeman, rector. Drogheda.\nAfter having l>een replaced in his\nfann*ihfc. tl*\u2018 Estates Commissioners,\nfrom which he was evicted alK>ut twen\nty-five years ago. the death has occur\nred at Kane, Co. Louth, of Mr. Patrick\n0Allan, who was prominent in the\nLand League agitation.\nThe death is re[H*rt\u00bb*d from Austra\nlia of the Rev. Michael Hanley, pastor\nof Molong. Deceased, who succumbed\nto pneumonia, was in his 58th year,\nand was a native of Okleastle, Co.\nMeath.\nDuring the gale which passed over\nNew Ross on Sunday portion of the\nstore, gutted some time ago by fire, col\nlapsed over on the premise* of Mr.\nCondon, licensed vintner, caving in the\nroof. Luckily the occupants were at\ntending Mass at the time.\nMr. George M. Kidd, grandson of\nMr. F. \\V. Kidd. Dundalk, who has\nalready given promise of a bright ca\nreer. has carried off the Townsend\nMemorial Prize, awarded by Trinity\nCollege to the student in the Junior\nFreshman year, gaining the highesr\nmarks in mathematics.\nA lecture on the Memoirs of Myles\nByrne has been delivered at Ennis\ncortliy by Mr. Stephen Owynn. M. P..\nat which Kev. Father Fitzhenry. Atlm.,\npresided. On the proposition of Mr.\nP. Byrne. J. I\\. seconded by Mr. T.\nBarry, a rote of thanks was passed to\nMr. Gwynn.\nOwing to an outbreak of fire at the\nresidence of Sir William Paul. Bart..\nR. M.. Rallyglan, Co. Wexford, the\nspacious hall, wiych had recently been\nrenovated, was destroyed, together\nwith two valuable oil paintings and\nother effects. Sea sand was used with\ngood results as a fire extinguisher.\nThe death has fiecurred at Skerries\nof Mr. J. Mack, who for many years\nwas Head Constable at Arklow, and\nwho was understood fo be one of the\noldest members of the Royal. Irish\nConstabulary. He joined the force in\n1844. and volunteered and served in\nthe Crimea.\nIt was stated at the meeting of the\nBalleece Quarry Co., Rathdruin, that\nthe profits for the year wort* \u00a3342\n11s. 2d. The sales were \u00a32.78-\", and\nthe expenses included \u00a31.127. wages,\nand \u00a3741* paidio.lhe Xiubiin a lid South\nCoast Railway Company for freight.\nDr. W. Taylor and Mr. Win. Corner\nford were re-elected directors.\nA fine of r\u00bbs. with 5s. costs lias been\nImposed at Lonugwood. County Meath.\nPetty Sessions, on Miss Bridget Mc\nCormick. Thomastown, County Kil\ndare. prosecuted by the Midland Rail\nway Company for leaving a carriage\nwhile Hie train was In motion at En\nfield station. James Roche, a signal\nman. stated she had a narrow escape,\nand he had to drag her out of danger.\nMessrs. Davys Turkey (chairman)\nand G. II. Miller. Land Sub-Commis\nsioners. have given decisions in 31\noriginating notices under the Laud Act\nheard by them at Rathdruin. In all\nbut a few eases substantial reductions\nwere made on the old rents, varying\nfrom 17 to 50 per cent. The most re\nmarkable of the decisions relates to\nthe case of Mrs. Elsie Hoare. landlord:\nSimon Cullen. Bon ab rock a. tenant,\nwhich was a second term application.\nThe old rent was \u00a3221 the Poor Law\nValuation, \u00a3300 15s., and the judicial\nrent lias now been fixed at \u00a3101 Os.\nrhe Drogheda Board ot Guardians\nhave passed a resolution declining to\ncall on Dr. Adrian to resign as was\nsuggested by the Local Government\nBoard, and stating that as regards his\nage. he was as well able to discharge\nhis duties as at any time, and during\nthe43 years that he was medical officer\nof the Workhouse there Was never a\ncomplaint against him.\nMr. P. J. Hogan, Local Government\nInspector, has opened an inquiry into\na scheme under the Laborers Acts\nformulated by the Drogheda District\nCouncil. Mr. Dowdall, the Clerk, said\nit was proposed to erect 54 cottages\nwith half-acre allotments. Already\nthey had built 13d cottages. Tin an\nnual loss to the Council for the cot\ntages was \u00a33b5 Os. 4d., or \u00a34 Is. to the\ncottage.\nMiss May Ormsby. daughter of Head\nConstable Ormsby. Newbridge, has se\ncured the gold medal for science at\nSt. Charles College, Kensington. Lon\ndon. as well as 92 per cent of the\nmarks for the entire subjects. This is\nsaid to be the highest percentage vet\ntaken at that College. Miss Ormshv\nhas already won a two years' schol\narship of \u00a350 at tin' College\nThe Abbey lei x Rural District Coun\ncil on Thursday decided to purchase a\nportrait of Davitt to be hung in the\nt ward room. being prepared to defray\nthe cost out of their own pockets, if the\nI^iejd Government Board refuses to\nsanction the expenditure. The sugges\ntion is that a picture of a former Lord\nde Ves.-i is to be removed to make\nroom for if, one Councillor saying it\nwhs time to have landlordism wijwd\nOUt.\nMuch regret has been evoked by the\ndeath at the Presentation Convent.\nPortarliQgton, of Sister Augustine.\nThe deceased Nun, who bad only reach\ned bar 37th year, was the youngest\ndaughter of the late Mr. Michael Bren\nnan. Crosspa trick, many of whose fam\nily have been given to the service of\nthe Church. Office and High Mass\nwere held in the Parochial Church,\nPortarliugton. after which the remains\nof Sister Augustine were Interred in\nthe Convent burial ground. The chief\nmourners were Rev. Martin Brennan.\nRev. Thomas Brennan. Messrs. K. ,T.\nand Michael Brennan (brothers) Mrs.\nHarney (sister). Rev. James Harney\n(nephew). Rev. M. Phelan. S. J.: Rev.\nT. Phelan, P. P.; Rev. Martin Phelan.\nProfessor: Rev. E. Hackett, C. C.. and\nRev. T. Hackett. P. P. (cousins).\nMUNSTER.\nA man named Patrick Murphy of\nTarmons, Watervllle. County Kerry,\nwho. disappeared from his residence on\nthe 3d inst., has been found at Bandon\nby tlie police.\nWide and sincere regret is felt in\nCork amongst a large circle of friends\nand acquaintances at the death of Mrs.\nX. Sisk, which took place at her resi\ndence, 1 Evergreen Villus. The funeral\non Sunday morning was very largely\nattended.\nA woman whose name is unknown\nhas been rescued from being drowned\nin the river desk at Farfanfore, Coun\nty Kerry. After being transferred to a\nneighbor\u2019s house first aid was applied,\nand after about an hour's efforts anima\ntion was restored.\nMiss Erne MacN'amara, a member of\nthe choir, attached to Monkstown\nChurch, County Cork, has been present\ned with a gold bangle, set with pearls\nand pink topaz, on the occasion of her\napproaching marriage.\nRev. Win. Casey, I*. P., Abbey reale,\nis now pronouuced out of all danger,\nand his parishioners and his many\nfriends elsewhere have been greatly\ngratified that he is on the way to re\ncovery.\nAt the desire of the Most Rev. Dr.\nSheehan, a Ladies\u2019 Visiting Society has\nbeen formed in St. Patrick\u2019s parish,\nWaterford, and it is understood that a\nsimilar society will be formed iu the\nother parishes, with a central executive.\nThe vellum of the Royal Humane So\nciety has been presented to Mr. Joseph\nO\u2019F'arrelJ, Limerick, for rescuing a boy\nfrom drowning in the -Shannon.\nThe body of a man named Meredith\nTrimble has been found dead at Deer\npark bridge, on the railway near Midle\nton, apparently having fallen off the\nbridge. lie was a pensioner from the\nIrish Mounted Police, and served in\nMidleton district during the Fenian ris\ning of \u2019b7.\nThe Illness of Rev. Fr. Casey. P. P.,\nAbbeyfeale, was referred to at Newcas\ntle West Branch of the Fsited Wish\nLeague by Mr. .T. P. O\u2019Connor, and the\nchairman. Mr. Thomas Hurley, J. P.,\nexpressed the sympathy of the meeting\nwith Fr. Casey, and hoped for his\nspeedy recovery.\nBy eleven to ten votes the Limerick\nCorporation decided to increase by Is.\nweekly the wages paid to 54 carters and\nsweepers. The vote will be questioned,\nit is stated, as one Councillor voting\nin the majority is said not to have his\nname on the burgess roll.\nThe death has taken place at Rally\ncommon, Xenagh, of Mary Richardson,\nwho had reached the age oi 102 years.\nMr. James Meagher, chairman of the\nBoard of Guardians, referring at the\nmeeting of the board to her death, said\nhe had never before seen three figures\non a coffin.\nAt Tliurles Petty Sessions a young\navail named James Dooley was sentenc\ned to fourteen months\u2019 imprisonment\nfor assaulting the police and window\nsmashing; and in default of findiug bail\nwas to be imprisoned for a further\ntwelve months. Dooley, who is a* na\ntive of the town, was described as a\nvery dangerous man.\nAt Youghal Petty Sessions a ease\nwas dismissed which was brought\nagainst John Gritliu Pilmore, a farmer,\nfor taking possession of a stray dog\nand not notifying the police. Mr. Hor\nner. It. M., said the case was the first\nof its kind, and he desired the public\nto know that anyone taking possession\nof a stray dog should notify the police\nimmediately.\nThe members of the Cork Rural Dis\ntrict Council have presented an illu\nminated address to Mr. John Collins,\nJ. P\u201e D. C.. on his retirement as rep\nresentative of the District Council on\nthe County Council. Mr. Win. McDon\nald, the chairman of the Council, wrote\nstating tliat Mr. Collins deserved recog\nnition for his constant attendance and\nwatchfulness of the business of the dis\ntrict.\nAt Newcastle West Branch of the\nl uited Irish League arrangements were\nmade in connection with the proposed\nmonster Home Rule Demonstration, the\ndate for which was left to the Secre\ntary and Father Casey to decide, and it\nwas arranged to invite Messrs. ,7. E.\nRedmond. John Dillon, J. G. Swift Mac\nNeill. J >pU Devlin and the local\nM. P.s.\nAs the T p. in. passenger train from\nWaterford to Cork was proceeding on\nits journey on Friday evening it ran\ninto some cattle trucks which had be\ncome disconnected from an outgoing\ngoods train at Carriganore. The im\npact was so severe that a number of\ncattle were killed. The trucks were\nsmashed, and the engine of the passen\nger train somewhat damaged, but no\npersonal injuries were sustained.\nArising out of the application for\n\u00a3325 compensation made by Mr. John\nHoimes, Athlunkard, to the Limerick\nNo. 2 District Council, for the burning\nof 100 tons of hay, Mr. O'Regan, Co. C..\nsaid it was only a short time since that\nall application had been made for a\nsum little short of \u00a31,000 for extra po\nlice because of one or two disturbed\nplaces, and an effort should be made to\ntiring the business home to bhe proper\nquarter, and have the money levied on\nthe district responsible.\nThe Belfast I*ub!ie Health Commit\ntee have submitted points to Mr. Bir\nred for inclusion In a bill which he is\nabout to introduce in the coming session\nof Parliament detailing with powers re\nquired by local authorities, including\ndispensaries for consumptives, control\nof milk supply from outside districts,\nand the insurance of sanitary officers in\ncase of sickness and death from infec\ntious diseases.\nl lie Cork Hoard of Guardians, on the\nmotion of Mr. I*. Lynch, have unani\nmously passed a resolution calling at\ntention to the First Lord of the Admir\nalty the substitution of Norway gran\nite for local limestone by the contractor\nfor the Haulbawline Dockyard exten\nsion, and asking that the preparation\nof cut stone be suspended for the pres\nent in order that an inquiry might be\nmade into the circumstances.\nAt Listowel Petty Sessions, John\nFitzmaurice, Ballingeragh, was fined\n20s and 20s costs for obstructing James\nMoloney, stationmaster at Lixnaw, in\nthe discharge of his duty, by assaulting\nhim. Mr. John Condon, solicitor, who\nprosecuted on behalf of the G. S. W.\nCo., stated that Fitzmaurice refused to\ngo out of the proper exit, but insisted\non getting out at the end of the plat\nform.\nThe promoters of the Mout Sion Ba\nzaar are to be congratulated on the suc\ncess which has crowned their efforts\nduring the past year. At a public\nmeeting in the City llall, Waterford, on\nFriday evening, the Brother Superior\nannounced the net proceeds amounted\nto \u00a32,285. Preparations of the Bazaar\nwere commenced in February last, and\nthus extended over a fieri oil of general\ndepression in trade. Notwithstanding\nthis, the popularity of the Christian\nBrothers\u2019 Schools in Waterford has en\nabled their devoted teachers to reduce\ntheir debt by this very large amount.\nULSTER.\nMr. Samuel J. Johnston, Assistant\nlerk of the Peace for County Tyrone,\nwas on Saturday appointed to the po\nsition of Commissioner for Oaths in\nthe Omagh district.\nOur Buncrana correspondent states\nthat although the bays in the Bosses\nare teeming with herring, not a single\nnet has been shot since Saturday three\nweeks, owing to the boisterous weather.\nBoats which attempted to brave the\nugly seas running were swamped on\nevery occasion.\nA girl, named Mary McHugh, of Fiu\ntona, County Donegal, has been return\ned for trial, charged with having by\nfalse pretences obtained money and or\nders for board and lodgings from cler\ngy. When charged, she wept, and said\nshe was told to do it.\nSympathetic references were made\nat Coleraine Board of Guardians to the\ndeath of Sir Ilervev Bruce, who was a\nmember of the Board for over fifty-five\nyears, and was chairman for over twen\nty years.\nTlie death is much regretted of Mr.\nFrancis Heron, Ardegon, Ivillyleagh,\nCounty Down, who was a large landed\nproprietor, and Who contested the Comi\nty Councillorshlp of Klllyleagh Divis\nion with Col. Sharimin-Crnwford.\nAt Fintona (County Tyrone) Petty\nSessions on Tuesday Richard Bell,\ncreamery manager, was returned for\ntrial on the charge of having assaulted\na servant girl named Fanny McCuteli\neon. Ball was allowed.\nThe question of whether tlie Master\nof the Belfast Uniou should receive an\nincrease of salary for the extra duties\nentailed on him in looking after the\n\u2022'Abbey'\u2019 Sanatorium in connection with\nthe workhouse, has been referred to a\ncommittee.\nI .Mr. jaines a. .uoore, v. r>., *u, uitu\nI suddenly c>ix Monday at Port-rush. De\nceased, who was a native of the Bush\nmills district, was well known through\nout North Antrim. He leaves a widow\nand daughter to mourn his loss.\nEarly on Wednesday morning a fire\nbroke out in a house occupied by three\nfamilies named Harvey, Doherty, and\nCannon, in Main road, Moville. All the\nfamilies were obliged to make good\ntheir escape in their night attire. The\nlower part of the premises was gutted,\nwhile Doherty and Cannon lost most of\ntheir household effects.\nA number of friends of Mr. and Mrs.\nH. C. Pentland, have met at Kilkeel\nand presented them with an address\nand silver coffee service, as a farewell\ncompliment on Mr. Pentland's transfer\nto the head office of the Belfast Bank\nin Belfast. The attendance included\nthe Bari and Countess of Kilmorey.\nRight Rev. Dr. Chadwick conducted\nan ordination service in St. Columb\u2019s\nCathedral. Derry, on Sunday, when\nIlev. W. E. C. Fleming. B. A., curate\nof Templemore (Derry), and Rev. J.\nDrury. B. A., curate of Christ Church\n(Derry), were ordained to the priest\niiood. Rev. Canon Haves, B. D.. rec\ntor of Templemore. was the preacher.\nThe death has occurred at the age of\nover a hundred years, of Mrs. Woods,\nBallynabury, County Tyrone, who was\nquite healthy up to a few days before\nher death, and until a few weeks ago\nwas able to walk about and take an in\nterest in farm work.\nThe Committee of the Tyrone County\nHospital have received a cheque for\n\u00a3.\u00bb0 fi\\>m Col. Burgess towards the ex\nlenses of providing electric light, and\n'apt. Lowry mentioned that that made\niir, contributed by Col. Burgess. The\ncommittee approved of an arrangement\nequalising the nursing staff from the\nreligious point of view.\nThe Coleraine Harbour Board at its\nlast meeting, after transacting neces\nsary financial business, adjourned in\ntoken of respect of the late .Sir II. Her\nvey Brnee. Bart. Tributes to the de\nceased's merits were paid by Major\nTorrens, II. M. V. I. (chairman), Mr.\nII. Barrie. M. I1.; Sir Wm. Baxter. .1.\nI\u2019., and Mr. Gribbon, .1. I*.\nBanbridge Presbytery, at its meeting\nin Second Annaglilone Presbyterian\nChurch, Rev. A. R. Foy. M. A. (.Moder\nator) presiding, passed a resolution\nprotesting against the action of the\nBoard of National Education, who are\ntile paymasters of the teachers, in en\ndeavoring to shirk responsibility in re\ngurd to them in case of accident.\nA line of \u00a310 was imposed at Roslea,\nCounty Fermanagh, on Janies Lanca\nshire, alias James Dobbin, charged with\nhaving in his possession a still head,\ncopper worm, and other instruments\nand materials used in the manufacture\nof illicit spirits. The police evidence\nshowed that they found the articles\nmentioned in defendant\u2019s house at Tat\ntymore, and there was a smell of dis\ntillation about the house.\nAt Derry the magistrates refused in\nformations in the case of Thomas Xich\nolls, mate of the vessel Renown, al\nready l>efore the court charged with\nthe manslaughter of Thomas Winters,\na seaman on board the same ship. De\nceased and Nicholls fought on the ves\nsel, and subsequently Winters was ad\nmitted to the local infirmary, where he\ndied from virulent blood poisoning.\nThere were no wounds on the man, and\nnothing to connect accused with liis\ndeath.\nJohn and Francis Hanley, Derry\neliree (Fermanagh), and Alexander\nPlunkett and Michael MeAloon, Derry\nadd, were, at New tow iibu tier, returned\nfor trial on charges of having, with\nothers, conspired to injure, molest, and\nannoy Thomas Me Elroy, James McBl\nroy. and Patrick Murphy, and with\nhaving circulated a threatening notice\nregarding the McElroys and Murphy.\nA barefooted tramp was discovered\nearly on Sunday morning in the li\ncensed premises of Mr. Patrick Reilly.\nBridge street. Cavan. lie had \u00a33 Ids\nGd in silver in his possession and cop\nper to the amount of \u00a31 12s 2d, which\nwere in a small box, were missing, and\nsubsequently the box and the coppers\nand the tramp\u2019s l>oots were found. A\nsmall vessel, known to tramps as a\n\u201cdrum,\u201d which apparently he carried,\nwas found on the counter half tilled\nwith whisky and tea leaves.\nThe interment has taken place in the\nCity Cemetery, Belfast^ of Mr. A. <1.\nRoddie, the greater part of whose life\nwas spent in teaching, first in Derry,\nand afterwards in the Academical In\nstitution, Coleraine, and finally in the\nMethodist College, Belfast, where he\nhad been Master for thirty-one years.\nOut of respect to his memory the col\nlege was closed, and the pupils and\nstaff attended the funeral.\nIt was slated at Belfast Citizens\u2019 As\nsociation by the chairman, II. S.\nWoods, .T. I*., that the ascertained loss\nso far over the defalcations in connec\ntion with portion of the city rate was\n\u00a35.000, but there was also a very large\namount to be added for rates uncol\nlected t^H*n property returned as va\ncant. Mr. Woods was re-elected as\npresident, and Mr. John Metrnw and\nMr. G. W. Ferguson, J. P\u201e honorable\nsecretaries, Mr. K. B. Walkington,\ntreasurer.\nFive children had a narrow escape\nfrom suffocation in a lire which broke\nout in the residence of their father, i\nMr. James McCall ion, in the North\nWard, Derry City. When the alarm\nwas raised the place was well alight,\nhut Mr. McCallion, after sustaining se\nvere burns, succeeded in rescuing the\nlittle ones, who all slept in the one\nroom. Everything in the house was\neither burned or destroyed by water.\n\u201cTo-day prisoner is the picture of\npenitence,\u201d remarked Mr. Macaulay, so\nlicitor, to Mr. Nagle. R. M., at Belfast,\nduring the hearing of a charge of ar\nson against Patrick Gilmore. The lat\nter was alleged to have set fire to Ills\nhouse in Upton street during a drinking\nbout, but the damage done was trifling.\nMr. Macaulay pleaded eloquently for\nleniency, as accused had turned over a\nnew leaf, and his worship adjourned\ni the ease for a fortnight.\nBelfast Guardians, in view of the\nlarge increase iu the unemployed ad\nmitted to the workhouse, discussed a\ni proposition made by Mr. Murphy that\na meeting of the Distress Committee\n1 should be held to consider the situation.\nMr. Murphy remarked that \u00a3200,000\nhad l>een set apart by the govemmeut\nin eonection with the Unemployed Act\nThe chairman said that he had been\nvice chairman of the Distress Commit\ntee. They had had \u00a3200 allocated to\nthem for the work, ami it had l>een\nswallowed up in salaries, and not a\npoor man got a shilling. He had. there\nfore. washed his hands out of the lot.\nThe further consideration of the mat\nter was adjourned, Mr. Murphy under\ntaking to make inquiries and bring the\nmatter up again.\nCONNAUGHT.\nThe Roscommon Board of Guardians\nand District Council have elected Mr.\nMichael Moran as Clerk of the Board\nand Council.\nTJie death has occurred at his resj\nilence. Poweisborough House. Tubber\neurry, of Mr. James J. Powell, J. 1*.\nDeceased, who had been ailing for a\nconsiderable time, was advanced in\nyears, and was a member of an old Co.\n.Sligo Catholic family,\ni John MeSharry 15, of Diffreeu,\n(Leitrim), disappeared from his home'\non Monday night. The hotly of the\nmissing youth was found ou Saturday\non the mountain about a mile from his\nhome by some engineers who are en\ngaged at work in the neighborhood.\nAt a concert and variety entertain\nmetn in St. Mary\u2019s Hall, Ballnghader\neen, in aid of the Sisters of Charity,\nthe Misses Thunder. Tighe, and Mur\nphy, three talented young Dublin la\ndies. achieved much success.\nThe Tuam Board of Guardians, in\ndeference to the wishes of tlie local\nSociety for the Suport of Home Man\nufactures, have decided that in future\ncontracts to accept so far as possible\nonly articles of Irish manufacture,\nand to insist on same bearing the Irish\ntrade mark.\nAt the Galway Docks on Saturday a\nblind man named Bourke, who has\npassed his 80th year, accidentally\nstumbled into three feet of water, lie\nwas rescued immediately and conveyed\nto the County Infirmary, hut died two\nhours later from shock and immer\nsion.\nThe Kilreecle branch l'. I. L. lias de\ncided to withhold financial support\nfrom the Irish party until unity is\nbrought about, and has passed a reso\nlution stating that no obstacle should\nbe placed in the way of Messrs. W.\nO\u2019Brien, T. M. Ilealy, and John O'Don\nnell returning to the party ranks.\nAt a special court at Carrigallen, Co.\nLeitrim, nine men were sent to jail for\none calendar month each for alleged\nunlawful assembly and riot at Carri\ngallen on the 18th of November, aris\ning out of cases of boycotting in the\nAughavns district. The action of the\ngovernment in. ordering the prosecu\ntion was condemned at a subsequent\npublic meeting.\nThe wife of a laborer. Martin Brer\nton. of Rathrnugban (Sligo), went out\nwith her husband\u2019s dinner, leaving a\nlittle girl of about 4 years of age alone\nin the house. On her return the wom\nan was horrified to find that the child\nhad fallen into the fire in her absence.\nThe little one was at once removed to\nSligo Workhouse Hospital, where it\ndied the next day.\nAn old woman named Catherine Mo\nhan. who has died an inmate of Ttiam\nWorkhouse, has left in the custody of a\nshopkeeper a savings hank deposit for\n\u00a300, with a will appointing Canon\nMacken administrator, and bequeath\ning \u00a350 for the poor of Tuain, and Can\non Macken has forwarded \u00a315 of the\nmoney to the guardians for the cost of\nher maintenance.\nIt has been deckled at a meeting in\nTuam of the Committees of the Gaelic\nLeague, United Irish League, National\nCouncil, Town Tenants\u2019 League, Tem\nperance Society to ask his Grace Most\nRev. Dr. Ilealy to preside at a public\nmeeting in support of Irish industries,\nand to request the clergy to deliver at\nleast one sermon on the subject. The\nmeeting also urged the Board of Guard\nians to aeeept only Irish goods when\nproviding the usual supplies.\nA successful Gaelic concert was held\nin Belclnre, Co. Galway, on Sunday\nnight. Among the contributors were\nseveral Oireachtas and Connacht Feis\nprize winners. An address in Irish\nwas delivered by Mr. Thomas O'Con\neannan, Ard Thimthire, and at the\nclose Father Xeary, C. 0., proposed a\nvote of thanks to the lecturer. It has\nbeen decided to start an Irish class\nimmediately.\nCaptain G. Wynne. I,. G. Board Au\nditor. has surcharged members of\nthe Ballinasloe Urban Council \u00a36.3 12s\n7d, and three of the rate collectors in\nsums of \u00a3512, \u00a3374 and \u00a324 respective\nly. The Auditor states that the mem\nbers are personally responsible for the\ncosts of the legal proceedings instituted\nby the Board of Works and County\nCouncil for failing to discharge the\namounts demanded by these bodies,\nand the rate collectors for not having\ntheir collection closer before the .31st\nof March.\nEDITOR PRESENTS REMEDY\nFOR THE FINANCIAL PANIC.\nC. P. J. Mooney Before Irish Fellow\nship Club Advocates Passage of\nLaws to Stop Bank Speculation.\nRemedies to end tbej^resent financial\npanic and to prevent fs repetition were\noffered by C. P. J. /looney. managing\neditor of William JjE Hearst\u2019s Chicago\nExaminer, in an ingress before tbe\nIrish Fellowship club Saturday.\nHe criticised /ryau's idea to have\nthe government guarantee the sound\nness of banks Aid declared that laws\nshould be pas#d \u201cto take the specula\ntors out of th/hanks and the banks out\nof speeulatirdL\u201d He also asked laws to\nlimit the diJaends of banks, to restrict\nthe businef in which various kinds of\nKngage, to stop the watering\nnd to have the government\nle interstate commerce cor\nient outlook in Congress is\nepubllcan members will\nsession trying to find out\nl wagon is going to the\ne, and to climb In.\u201d he said,\nerats will do nothing but\nfloor and try to prove that\noriginal Bryan man.\u201d\nling of Rockford, candidate\n_ ublican nomination for Sec\nretary of State, also spoke. Judge El\nbridge Haoecy presided.","height":"22288","width":"16000"}}
